\title{Generalized multicategories}
\taxon{doctrine}
\import{macros}

\p{Depending on the choice of monad, a \nlab{generalized multicategory} could be
a [multicategory](dct-000A), a symmetric multicategory, a cartesian
multicategory, or something more exotic. Our axiomatization of these doctrines
as a modal double theory is reminiscent of
[Cruttwell-Shulman's](cruttwell-shulman-2010) definition but bypasses the
complicated construction of the "horizontal Kleisli virtual double category" of
a monad on a virtual double category.}

\p{The generalized multicategories axiomatized here are "normalized," in
Cruttwell-Shulman's jargon, but see also the [unnormalized notion](dct-000N).}

\transclude{thy-000F}

\subtree{
  \title{Models of the theory of generalized multicategories}
  \taxon{proposition}

  \p{A model of the modal theory #{(\dbl{T}, T)} of generalized multicategories
  in #{(\dbl{S}, S)}, where \dbl{S} is a virtual equipment and #{S: \dbl{S} \to
  \dbl{S}} is a monad in VDCs, is precisely a \em{normalized}
  #{S}-multicategory.}

  \p{In particular, a model...
  \ul{
    \li{...in #{(\SSet, \List)} is exactly a multicategory}
    \li{...in #{(\SSet, \ListSym)} is exactly a symmetric multicategory}
    \li{...in #{(\SSet, \ListCart)} is exactly a cartesian multicategory.}
  }
  }

  \proof{
  \p{A model consists, first of all, of a category object #{X} in \dbl{S} and a
  profunctor #{P: S(X) \proto X}. By the composition axiom, we can define a cell
  #{\gamma} in \dbl{T} as:
  \centerfigs{
  \quiverinline{
  % https://q.uiver.app/#
  \begin{tikzcd}
	{T^2 x} & Tx & x \\
	Tx && x
	\arrow["Tp"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["{\mu_x}"', from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["p"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-3, to=2-3]
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "p"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=2-1, to=2-3]
	\arrow["\gamma"{description, pos=0.4}, draw=none, from=1-2, to=0]
  \end{tikzcd}
  }
  #{\qquad\coloneqq\qquad}
  \quiverinline{
  % https://q.uiver.app/#
  \begin{tikzcd}
	{T^2 x} & Tx & x \\
	{T^2 x} && x \\
	Tx && x
	\arrow["Tp"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["p"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-3, to=2-3]
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{(\mu_x)_! \odot p}"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=2-1, to=2-3]
	\arrow["{\mu_x}"', from=2-1, to=3-1]
	\arrow[equals, from=2-3, to=3-3]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "p"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=3-1, to=3-3]
	\arrow["{\mathrm{comp}}"{description, pos=0.4}, draw=none, from=1-2, to=0]
	\arrow["{\mathrm{res}}"{description, pos=0.6}, draw=none, from=0, to=1]
  \end{tikzcd}
  }
  }

  The image of this cell in \dbl{S} defines the composition operation of the
  multicategory; conversely, by the universal property of restriction, choosing
  the multicategory's composition operation uniquely determines the image of the
  composition cell on the right-hand side.}

  \p{By the normalization axiom, the morphisms of #{X} are in isomorphism with
  the \em{unary} morphisms in #{P}. Moreover, by the formula for restrictions in
  a virtual equipment ([CS10](cruttwell-shulman-2010), Theorem 7.16), we have
  the equation

  \centerfigs{
  \quiverinline{
  % https://q.uiver.app/#
  \begin{tikzcd}
	x & x & x \\
	Tx & x & x \\
	Tx && x
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{\id_x}"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["{\eta_x}"', from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{\id_x}"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-3, to=2-3]
	\arrow[""{name=2, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "p"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=2-1, to=2-2]
	\arrow[equals, from=2-1, to=3-1]
	\arrow[""{name=3, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{\id_x}"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=2-2, to=2-3]
	\arrow[equals, from=2-3, to=3-3]
	\arrow[""{name=4, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "p"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=3-1, to=3-3]
	\arrow["{\text{res}}"{description}, draw=none, from=0, to=2]
	\arrow["1"{description}, draw=none, from=1, to=3]
	\arrow["{\text{comp}}"{description, pos=0.4}, draw=none, from=2-2, to=4]
  \end{tikzcd}
  }
  #{\qquad=\qquad}
  \quiverinline{
  % https://q.uiver.app/#
  \begin{tikzcd}
	x & x & x \\
	x && x \\
	Tx && x
	\arrow["{\id_x}"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["{\id_x}"{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[equals, from=1-3, to=2-3]
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{\id_x}"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=2-1, to=2-3]
	\arrow["{\eta_x}"', from=2-1, to=3-1]
	\arrow[equals, from=2-3, to=3-3]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "p"'{inner sep=.8ex}, "\shortmid"{marking}, from=3-1, to=3-3]
	\arrow["{\text{comp}}"{description, pos=0.4}, draw=none, from=1-2, to=0]
	\arrow["{\text{res}}"{description, pos=0.6}, draw=none, from=0, to=1]
  \end{tikzcd}
  }
  }

  which (in conjunction with the compatibility axiom for the right action)
  proves that the \em{category} #{X} is isomorphic to the category of unary
  morphisms in #{P}. The two compatibility axioms further show that the left and
  right actions of #{X} on #{P} are fixed by the multicategory's composiiton
  operation.}

  \p{Finally, the associativity law of the multicategory is proved exactly as in
  the [unnormalized case](dct-000N).}

  }
}
